<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,151,897]" pageId="8" pageNumber="144">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,293,151,177]" pageId="8" pageNumber="144">Female.</emphasis>
Similar in shape and size to the male (
<figureCitation box="[733,803,151,177]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1966,1990]" captionTargetBox="[152,1434,525,1942]" captionTargetId="figure-206@6.[151,1436,525,1943]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 4. Cratomelus armatus female habitus. A. Lateral and B. Dorsal views respectively." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6919896" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6919896/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="144">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
). Tegmina rounded, both in the costal and anal margins, venation with a similar organization to the male (
<figureCitation box="[724,817,186,213]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[227,1362,185,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-28@7.[225,1362,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 5. Cratomelus armatus female. A. Tegmina. B. Hind wing. C. Terminalia axial view. D. Subgenital plate. E. Terminalia lateral view. (The white arrows in figures A and B, show the wing veins modification)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6919902" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6919902/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="144">Fig. 5A</figureCitation>
). Hindwing with specialized venation similarly to the male (
<figureCitation box="[221,310,222,249]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[227,1362,185,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-28@7.[225,1362,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 5. Cratomelus armatus female. A. Tegmina. B. Hind wing. C. Terminalia axial view. D. Subgenital plate. E. Terminalia lateral view. (The white arrows in figures A and B, show the wing veins modification)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6919902" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6919902/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="144">Fig. 5B</figureCitation>
). Posterior margin of the 7th and 8th tergites in the central portion moderately elevated, 10th tergite with a depression in the dorsal central area (
<figureCitation box="[662,752,258,285]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[227,1362,185,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-28@7.[225,1362,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 5. Cratomelus armatus female. A. Tegmina. B. Hind wing. C. Terminalia axial view. D. Subgenital plate. E. Terminalia lateral view. (The white arrows in figures A and B, show the wing veins modification)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6919902" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6919902/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="144">Fig. 5C</figureCitation>
). Epiproctus semicircle-shaped; below those, the paraprocts are flattened, sclerotized, and surrounding the excretory pore (
<figureCitation box="[848,937,294,321]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[227,1362,185,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-28@7.[225,1362,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 5. Cratomelus armatus female. A. Tegmina. B. Hind wing. C. Terminalia axial view. D. Subgenital plate. E. Terminalia lateral view. (The white arrows in figures A and B, show the wing veins modification)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6919902" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6919902/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="144">Fig. 5C</figureCitation>
). Subgenital plate triangular wider than long (
<figureCitation box="[159,248,330,357]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[227,1362,185,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-28@7.[225,1362,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 5. Cratomelus armatus female. A. Tegmina. B. Hind wing. C. Terminalia axial view. D. Subgenital plate. E. Terminalia lateral view. (The white arrows in figures A and B, show the wing veins modification)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6919902" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6919902/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="144">Fig. 5D</figureCitation>
). Cerci without modification, thin and medium size. Ovipositor as long as two-thirds the length of the hind femur, dorsal and ventral borders smooth, slightly curving upwards, apex slightly pointed (
<figureCitation box="[1169,1255,366,393]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[227,1362,185,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-28@7.[225,1362,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 5. Cratomelus armatus female. A. Tegmina. B. Hind wing. C. Terminalia axial view. D. Subgenital plate. E. Terminalia lateral view. (The white arrows in figures A and B, show the wing veins modification)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6919902" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6919902/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="144">Fig. 5E</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
